824. Med Decis Making. 1984;4(3):315-29. doi: 10.1177/0272989X8400400307.

Preferences for health outcomes. Comparison of assessment methods.

Read JL, Quinn RJ, Berwick DM, Fineberg HV, Weinstein MC.

This study compared standard gamble (SG), time trade-off (TTO), and category 
scaling (CS) methods for assessing preferences among hypothetical outcomes of 
coronary artery bypass surgery. High correlations among assessment methods, as 
found in some previous studies, do not assure the absence of systematic 
differences in rating obtained by different methods. This study used analysis of 
variance to test for differences among the three assessment methods. 
Questionnaire responses were obtained from 67 of 109 physicians participating in 
a postgraduate course on clinical decision making, following a lecture and 
workshop on utility theory. SG and CS were used to rate multivariate 
combinations of angina (none, moderate, and severe) and survival (0, 5, and 10 
years); and SG, TTO, and CS were used to rate univariate outcomes with angina 
(none, moderate, and severe) for the remainder of their life expectancy. SG 
ratings were higher than TTO ratings, which were higher than CS ratings (p less 
than 0.001 for all comparisons). Multivariate responses revealed a significant 
interaction between angina and survival dimensions using CS, but not using SG. 
We conclude that these methods are not interchangeable and that differences 
between SG and CS require a more complex explanation than differences in 
attitude toward risk.

DOI: 10.1177/0272989X8400400307
PMID: 6335216 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


