Colonic interposition for esophageal substitution.

Postlethwait RW.

Sufficient information has now accumulated to permit a better definition of the 
role of colonic interposition for substitution of the esophagus. For children 
and young adults with a long life expectancy, the interposed colon provides a 
well-functioning and durable conduit. When the stomach cannot be used, the colon 
is the best alternative in most patients. Necrosis of the colon remains the most 
frequent fatal complication; leakage and stenosis of the proximal anastomosis 
remain problems. Although results of the usual radiologic examinations with 
barium show that the colon empties by gravity, manometric results may 
demonstrate progressive peristalsis, particularly in response to stimulus from a 
bolus of dilute acid.

